{"name":"Mathlib.Analysis.Calculus.FDerivSymmetric","instances":[],"imports":["Init","Mathlib.Analysis.Calculus.MeanValue"],"declarations":[{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/FDerivSymmetric.lean#L324-L326","name":"second_derivative_symmetric","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/FDerivSymmetric.html#second_derivative_symmetric","doc":"If a function is differentiable, and has two derivatives at `x`, then the second\nderivative is symmetric. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/FDerivSymmetric.lean#L311-L319","name":"second_derivative_symmetric_of_eventually","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/FDerivSymmetric.html#second_derivative_symmetric_of_eventually","doc":"If a function is differentiable around `x`, and has two derivatives at `x`, then the second\nderivative is symmetric. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/FDerivSymmetric.lean#L261-L306","name":"Convex.second_derivative_within_at_symmetric","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/FDerivSymmetric.html#Convex.second_derivative_within_at_symmetric","doc":"If a function is differentiable inside a convex set with nonempty interior, and has a second\nderivative at a point of this convex set, then this second derivative is symmetric. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/FDerivSymmetric.lean#L236-L256","name":"Convex.second_derivative_within_at_symmetric_of_mem_interior","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/FDerivSymmetric.html#Convex.second_derivative_within_at_symmetric_of_mem_interior","doc":"Assume that `f` is differentiable inside a convex set `s`, and that its derivative `f'` is\ndifferentiable at a point `x`. Then, given two vectors `v` and `w` pointing inside `s`, one\nhas `f'' v w = f'' w v`. Superseded by `Convex.second_derivative_within_at_symmetric`, which\nremoves the assumption that `v` and `w` point inside `s`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/FDerivSymmetric.lean#L182-L229","name":"Convex.isLittleO_alternate_sum_square","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/FDerivSymmetric.html#Convex.isLittleO_alternate_sum_square","doc":"One can get `f'' v w` as the limit of `h ^ (-2)` times the alternate sum of the values of `f`\nalong the vertices of a quadrilateral with sides `h v` and `h w` based at `x`.\nIn a setting where `f` is not guaranteed to be continuous at `f`, we can still\nget this if we use a quadrilateral based at `h v + h w`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/FDerivSymmetric.lean#L71-L175","name":"Convex.taylor_approx_two_segment","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Analysis/Calculus/FDerivSymmetric.html#Convex.taylor_approx_two_segment","doc":"Assume that `f` is differentiable inside a convex set `s`, and that its derivative `f'` is\ndifferentiable at a point `x`. Then, given two vectors `v` and `w` pointing inside `s`, one can\nTaylor-expand to order two the function `f` on the segment `[x + h v, x + h (v + w)]`, giving a\nbilinear estimate for `f (x + hv + hw) - f (x + hv)` in terms of `f' w` and of `f'' ‚¨ù w`, up to\n`o(h^2)`.\n\nThis is a technical statement used to show that the second derivative is symmetric. "}]}